Renamed_data = pd.DataFrame()
Renamed_data['CheckingAccountStatus'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['CheckingAccountStatus'].map({'A14':'none','A11':'lt.0','A12':'0.to.200','A13':'gt.200'}))

Renamed_data['CreditHistory'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['CreditHistory'].map({'A30':'NoCredit.AllPaid','A31':'ThisBank.AllPaid','A32':'PaidDuly','A33':'Delay','A34':'Critical'}))

Renamed_data['Purpose']= pd.Categorical(full_data['Purpose'].map({'A40':'NewCar','A41':'UsedCar','A42':'Furniture.Equipment','A43':'Radio.Television','A44':'DomesticAppliances','A45':'Repairs','A46':'Education','A47':'Vacation','A48':'Retiring','A49':'Business','A410':'Others'}))

Renamed_data['SavingsAccountBonds'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['SavingsAccountBonds'].map({'A61':'lt.100','A62':'100.to.500','A63':'500.to.1000','A64':'gt.1000','A65':'Unknown'}))

Renamed_data['EmploymentDuration'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['EmploymentDuration'].map({'A71':'Unemployed','A72':'0.to.1','A73':'1.to.4','A74':'4.to.7','A75':'gt.7'}))

full_data['Personal'] = full_data['Personal'].map({'A91':'MDivorced.Seperated','A92':'FNotSingle','A93':'MSingle','A94':'MMarried.Widowed','A95':'FSingle'})
Renamed_data['Sex'] = pd.Categorical(full_data.Personal.str[0])
Renamed_data['MaritalStatus'] = pd.Categorical(full_data.Personal.str[1:])
Renamed_data['OtherDebtorsGuarantors'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['OtherDebtorsGuarantors'].map({'A101':'None','A102':'CoApplicant','A103':'Guarantor'}))

Renamed_data['Property'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['Property'].map({'A121':'RealEstate','A122':'Insurance', 'A123':'CarsOthers','A124':'Unknown'}))

Renamed_data['OtherInstallmentPlans'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['OtherInstallmentPlans'].map({'A141':'Bank','A142':'Stores','A143':'None'}))

Renamed_data['Housing'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['Housing'].map({'A151':'Rent','A152':'Own','A153':'ForFree'}))

Renamed_data['Job'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['Job'].map({'A171':'UnemployedUnskilled','A172':'UnskilledResident','A173':'SkilledEmployee','A174':'Management.SelfEmp.HighlyQualified'}))

Renamed_data['Telephone'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['Telephone'].map({'A191':0,'A192':1}))

Renamed_data['ForeignWorker'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['ForeignWorker'].map({'A201':1,'A202':0}))

Age_interval = (0,25,40,60,65,100)
categ = ['Student','Young','Adult','MidSenior','Senior']
Renamed_data['Age'] = full_data['Age']
Renamed_data['AgeBin'] = pd.cut(full_data.Age,Age_interval,labels=categ)
#data[['sex']] = data[['Personal']].apply(lambda x:x.split('_')[0])
month_interval = (0,12,24,36,48,60,72,84)
length = ['lt.1','1.to.2','2.to.3','3.to.4','4.to.5','5.to.6','6.to.7']
Renamed_data['Duration'] = full_data['Duration']
Renamed_data['DurationBin'] = pd.cut(full_data.Duration,month_interval,labels=length)
Renamed_data['InstallmentRatePercentage'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['InstallmentRatePercentage'].map({1:'1',2:'2',3:'3',4:'4'}))
Renamed_data['ResidenceDuration'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['ResidenceDuration'].map({1:'1',2:'2',3:'3',4:'4'}))
Renamed_data['NumberExistingCredits'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['NumberExistingCredits'].map({1:'1',2:'2',3:'3',4:'4'}))
Renamed_data['NumberPeopleMaintenance'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['NumberPeopleMaintenance'].map({1:'1',2:'2'}))

credit_interval = (0,500,1000,1500,2500,5000,7500,10000,15000,20000,30000)
credit = ['0.to.500','500.to.1000','1000.to.1500','1500.to.2500','2500.to.5000','5000.to.7500','7500.to.10000','10000.to.15000','15000.to.20000','20000.to.30000']
Renamed_data['AmountBin']=pd.cut(full_data.Amount,credit_interval,labels=credit)
Renamed_data['Amount'] = full_data['Amount']
Renamed_data['Class'] = pd.Categorical(full_data['Class'].map({1:'Good',2:'Bad'}))

Conclusion:¶

  • Classification accuracy is the easiest classification metric to understand,

  • But, it does not tell you the underlying distribution of response values.

  • We examine by calculating the null accuracy.

  • And, it does not tell you what "types" of errors your classifier is making

Confusion matrix¶

In [74]:
# IMPORTANT: first argument is true values, second argument is predicted values
# this produces a 2x2 numpy array (matrix)
print(metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_class))

[[183  31]
 [ 38  48]]

Every observation in the testing set is represented in exactly one box.¶

  • It's a 2x2 matrix because there are 2 response classes

  • The format shown here is not universal

  • Take attention to the format when interpreting a confusion matrix

Basic terminology¶

  • True Positives (TP): we correctly predicted that they are bad loans
    • 183
  • True Negatives (TN): we correctly predicted that they are good loans
    • 48
  • False Positives (FP): we incorrectly predicted that they are bad loan (a "Type I error")
    • 38
    • Falsely predict positive
    • Type I error
  • False Negatives (FN): we incorrectly predicted that they are good loan (a "Type II error")
    • 31
    • Falsely predict negative
    • Type II error
  • 1: Postive class (Good Loans)
  • 2: Negative class (Bad Loans)

Metrics computed from a confusion matrix¶

  • Classification Accuracy: Overall, how often is the classifier correct?
In [79]:
# use float to perform true division, not integer division

0.77

Classification Error: Overall, how often is the classifier incorrect?¶

  • Also known as "Misclassification Rate"
In [80]:
classification_error = (FP + FN) / float(TP + TN + FP + FN)

print(classification_error)
print(1 - metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_class))

0.23
0.22999999999999998

Sensitivity: When the actual value is positive, how often is the prediction correct?

* Something we want to maximize
* How "sensitive" is the classifier to detecting positive instances?
* Also known as "True Positive Rate" or "Recall"
* TP / all positive
* all positive = TP + FN
In [81]:
sensitivity = TP / float(FN + TP)

print(sensitivity)
print(metrics.recall_score(y_test, y_pred_class,labels=[2.,1.]))

0.8551401869158879
0.8551401869158879

  • Specificity: When the actual value is negative, how often is the prediction correct?

  • Something we want to maximize

    • How "specific" (or "selective") is the classifier in predicting positive instances?
    • TN / all negative
      • all negative = TN + FP
In [82]:
specificity = TN / (TN + FP)

print(specificity)

0.5581395348837209
  • False Positive Rate : When the actual value is negative, how often is the prediction incorrect?
In [83]:
false_positive_rate = FP / float(TN + FP)

print(false_positive_rate)
print(1 - specificity)

0.4418604651162791
0.4418604651162791

Precision: When a positive value is predicted, how often is the prediction correct?

* How "precise" is the classifier when predicting positive instances?
In [84]:
precision = TP / float(TP + FP)

print(precision)
print(metrics.precision_score(y_test, y_pred_class))

0.8280542986425339
0.8280542986425339

  • Many other metrics can be computed: F1 score, Matthews correlation coefficient, etc.

  • Conclusion:

    • Confusion matrix gives you a more complete picture of how your classifier is performing
    • Also allows you to compute various classification metrics, and these metrics can guide your model selection.

  • Bad loan detector (positive class is "Bad"):

    • Optimize for sensitivity
    • FN as a variable
    • Because false positives (normal loans that are flagged as possible bad loan) are more acceptable than false negatives (bad loans that are not detected)

    • Prioritize work on those with a higher probability

    • Choose the class with the highest probability

    • Class 2 is predicted if probability > 0.5
    • Class 1 is predicted if probability < 0.5

In [106]:
def cost(confusion,cost_FN,cost_FP):
    TN = confusion[1, 1]
    TP = confusion[0, 0]
    FN = confusion[1, 0]
    FP = confusion[0, 1]
    false_positive_rate = FP / float(TP + FP)
    false_negative_rate = FN / float(TN+FN)
    return ((false_positive_rate)*cost_FP+false_negative_rate*cost_FN)
In [107]:
print(cost(confusion,5,1))

2.3541621386655076
In [108]:
print(cost(metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_class),5,1))

1.2096283416648554

Conclusion:

* Threshold of 0.5 is used by default (for binary problems) to convert predicted probabilities into class predictions
* Threshold can be adjusted to increase sensitivity or specificity
* Sensitivity and specificity have an inverse relationship
* Increasing one would always decrease the other
* Adjusting the threshold should be one of the last step you do in the model-building process
    * The most important steps are
    * Building the models
    * Selecting the best model

# we do not use y_pred_class, because it will give incorrect results without generating an error
# roc_curve returns 3 objects fpr, tpr, thresholds
# fpr: false positive rate
# tpr: true positive rate
fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob_good,pos_label=1)

plt.plot(fpr, tpr)
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 12
plt.title('ROC curve for loan classifier')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity)')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (Sensitivity)')
plt.grid(True)

# define a function that accepts a threshold and prints sensitivity and specificity
def evaluate_threshold(threshold):
    print('Sensitivity:', tpr[thresholds > threshold][-1])
    print('Specificity:', 1 - fpr[thresholds > threshold][-1])
